<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 3:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I260dc1c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>3.</label.designator><headtext>Statutory Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f2cc6682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>3:3.</label.designator><headtext>Spousal privilege—Criminal cases</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The case of <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1980105854" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie05b1c927fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Trammel v. U.S.</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic215d3007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] which established the rule that a spouse may choose whether to testify against another in a criminal case was a departure from both proposed <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="USFRER505" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Ie05cf1507fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 505</cite.query> and historical federal precedent, both of which would have barred adverse testimony of one spouse absent the consent of both. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05cf1517fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> carves out a special marital privilege recognized in criminal cases which is different from the privilege created in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05cf1527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query> because it addresses the compellability of one spouse to become a witness for or against another in a criminal proceeding and not the admissibility of evidence.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic215d3017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] The statute provides that a <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[h]usband and wife … shall not be compellable to give evidence in any criminal proceed<page no="50"/>ing for or against each other.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic215fa107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] Thus, the spouse of a criminal defendant has a privilege not to testify for or against the defendant spouse in any criminal proceeding. <eos/><bos/>The privilege belongs to the witness spouse alone and cannot be claimed by the defendant spouse.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic215fa117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] Likewise, only the witness spouse may waive the privilege.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Waiver of the privilege need not be express. <eos/><bos/>The spouse waives any right to claim privilege under <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05f14307fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> when she voluntarily takes the stand, even if she does so as a defense witness.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic21621217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] Under such circumstances, she will be subject to cross examination by the prosecution[<footnote.reference refid="Ic21648307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] and the court is under no obligation to advise the witness of her right to claim privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic21648327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Because the defendant cannot compel his spouse to testify, it is grounds for a mistrial if the district attorney comments on the failure of the defendant&apos;s wife to testify.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2166f407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] It may also be reversible error to require the testifying spouse to claim the privilege within the hearing of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2166f417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] The election of the spouse not to testify against the defendant should be made out of the presence of the jury.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic2166f427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] However, it is not error if defense counsel could have avoided public invocation of the privilege by requesting that the matter be addressed outside the presence of the jury when <page no="51"/>the testifying spouse took the stand and was expected to claim privilege.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic21696507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Unlike the spousal privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie062bdb07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query>, the privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie062bdb17fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query> is not permanent and does <ital>not</ital> survive divorce or death of a spouse.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic21696517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>] When a claim of privilege is made pursuant to this section, the witness must be lawfully married to the defendant at the time of the trial. <eos/><bos/>It is irrelevant when the communication was made or whether it was intended to be confidential.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Because no other privilege sweeps as broadly, savvy criminal defendants have been known to marry a potential witness for the sole reason of gaining the benefits of the privilege at trial. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals has held that the marital privilege provided by this section&apos;s predecessor, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-23" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie06381007fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-23</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic216bd607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13</footnote.reference>] may be invoked regardless of any underlying motives for the marriage.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic216bd617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14</footnote.reference>] The proponent of the privilege is only required to show that a valid, legal marriage exists.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>No marital privilege exists in cases in which the husband or wife is charged with a crime against a minor child[<footnote.reference refid="Ic216bd627fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">15</footnote.reference>] or his or her spouse (pursuant to a lawful marriage).<eos/><bos/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic216bd637fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">16</footnote.reference>] In such cases, the privilege is waived only with respect to evidence on the specific act for which the defendant is charged.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic216e4707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">17</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic215d3007fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1980105854" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Ie05b6ab27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Trammel v. U.S., 445 U.S. 40, 100 S. Ct. 906, 63, 63 L. Ed. 2d 186, 5 Fed. R. Evid. Serv. 737 (1980)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic215d3017fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985154459" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05d3f707fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Chadwick v. State, 176 Ga. App. 296, 335 S.E.2d 674 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="50"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic215fa107fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05d8d907fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic215fa117fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1974128555" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05e02c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Young v. State, 232 Ga. 285, 206 S.E.2d 439 (1974)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1984105300" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05e02c57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ballard v. State, 252 Ga. 53, 311 S.E.2d 453 (1984)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1991100406" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05e02c87fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Brown v. State, 199 Ga. App. 188, 404 S.E.2d 469 (1991)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05e02cb7fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Biswas v. State, 255 Ga. App. 339, 565 S.E.2d 531 (2002)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, the defendant spouse does still have a right to claim privilege with respect to any confidential communications. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05e9f007fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501</cite.query>; <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="GAEVIDENCES3:2" w-pub-number="160247" ID="Ic21621207fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">§ 3:2</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000360" ID="Ie05e9f017fbf11ea988285db8533e975">supra.</cite.query></paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic21621217fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05f3b427fbf11ea988285db8533e975">White v. State, 211 Ga. App. 694, 440 S.E.2d 68 (1994)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="2002294923" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05f3b457fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Biswas v. State, 255 Ga. App. 339, 565 S.E.2d 531 (2002)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic21648307fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie05ffe927fbf11ea988285db8533e975">White v. State, 211 Ga. App. 694, 440 S.E.2d 68 (1994)</cite.query>, holding that the testifying wife waived privilege when she voluntarily took the stand as defense witness and was subject to a thorough cross-examination. <eos/><bos/>However, this has no effect on the marital privilege recognized in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05ffe937fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501(a)(1)</cite.query> under which the spouse would still be entitled to claim privilege of confidential marital communications, if applicable. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-501" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie05ffe947fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-501</cite.query> and <cite.query w-ref-type="DA" w-normalized-cite="GAEVIDENCES3:2" w-pub-number="160247" ID="Ic21648317fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">§ 3:2</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994055307" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000360" ID="Ie05ffe957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">supra.</cite.query></paratext><eos/><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic21648327fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1979128344" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie06073c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Wiley v. State, 150 Ga. App. 607, 258 S.E.2d 286 (1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1989126536" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie06073c57fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Mapp v. State, 191 Ga. App. 622, 382 S.E.2d 618 (1989)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2166f407fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982107878" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000849" ID="Ie060e8f37fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Ferry v. State, 161 Ga. App. 795, 287 S.E.2d 732, 26 A.L.R.4th 1 (1982)</cite.query> (district attorney&apos;s comment on the failure of the defendant&apos;s wife to testify was grounds for a mistrial in the absence of any curative action by the trial court).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2166f417fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985148585" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie0615e227fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Price v. State, 175 Ga. App. 780, 334 S.E.2d 711 (1985)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1983151865" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie0615e257fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Wynn v. State, 168 Ga. App. 132, 308 S.E.2d 392 (1983)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982117938" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie0615e287fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Westbrook v. State, 162 Ga. App. 130, 290 S.E.2d 333 (1982)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1976144251" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie0615e2b7fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Colson v. State, 138 Ga. App. 366, 226 S.E.2d 154 (1976)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic2166f427fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1982117938" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie061fa627fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Westbrook v. State, 162 Ga. App. 130, 290 S.E.2d 333 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="51"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic21696507fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1992069296" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie06248827fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Patterson v. State, 202 Ga. App. 440, 414 S.E.2d 895 (1992)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic21696517fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1985154459" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie062e4c27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Chadwick v. State, 176 Ga. App. 296, 335 S.E.2d 674 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic216bd607fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Repealed effective January 1, 2013.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic216bd617fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-serial-number="1994140370" w-seq-number="00034" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ie063f6327fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Peters, 213 Ga. App. 352, 444 S.E.2d 609 (1994)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic216bd627fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>15</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00035" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie06492707fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(1)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic216bd637fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>16</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00036" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie064e0907fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(2)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic216e4707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>17</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018100" w-seq-number="00037" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-5-503" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Ie0652eb07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-5-503(b)(1)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 3:3<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
